Use internal slave pool for build jobs with null label

If a build job configuration has a null label, the job will run on the
internal slave pool.  If it has a label, it will run on a compute VM
with a template identifier matching that label.

BuildSlave instances now use the EXCLUSIVE mode, which prevents builds
that have a null label (and should therefore run on the internal slave
pool) from running on a compute VM.

20087:  call regional compute api to get full list of compute endpoints

Added API to get the compute service zones for a DCS organization, and
to get a ComputeService for a specific zone.

The build service now uses the new API to always start build VMs in the
preferred compute zone.  If a VM errors out, it is fully stopped.  The
next attempt to start the VM will again get the preferred zone, which
may have changed.  It will use the new zone to start the VM on that
attempt.

It is now possible to have VMs running in a number of zones, so the zone
where each VM instance was started is recorded in the database.

The management of SSH keys had to change, such that each VM instance now
has its own SSH key definition, rather than there being just one SSH key
in the compute account.  This ensures that there is an SSH key available
to the instance no matter what zone it is started in, and that the SSH
keys are cleaned up when all instances are removed from a zone.

Periodically sync the list of provisioned slaves between hub and hmaster

The list of slaves that are currently provisioned and in use by the
hmaster could get out of sync between the hub and hmaster.  For example,
this could happen if the hmaster restarted, at which time it loses its
internal list of slaves.  But those slaves are still marked as being in
use in the hub profile database.  The hmaster will now call the hub
periodically to get the list of slaves it thinks are in use by the
hmaster, and deprovision any that are no longer in use.

Implement latest changes to compute service API

Improvements to the compute service API based on the latest spec:

* X-Oracle-Compute-Call-Id header added to ComputeServiceException.
This allows a failing compute call to be associated with an ID from the
compute service, which may be used to diagnose problems.  If present,
the ID is part of the exception message, and is available through a new
getComputeCallId() method.

* Implement support for user impersonation using the X-Oracle-Compute-As
header.  This should allow DCS to call the compute service on behalf of
tenants, using an internal APPID to authenticate but running the command
as a tenant user.

* Update JSON types from nimbula to oracle-compute.

Add PrivateComputeSecIpEntry property to ComputeServicePropertyProvider.

 - The new property defines the IP range of incoming traffic from the Private Compute.

 - The secipentry is currently used by Develop VM orchestration to create a secrule
   to permit incoming traffic from Private Compute and block traffic from other sources.

 - ComputeServicePropertyProviderBean reads the value from the
   "oracle.compute.service.private.compute.secipentry" config property.

 - The default value is 0.0.0.0/0 if the property is not specified in c2c-env file.

Use boot from NDS for compute build VMs

Boot from NDS is now used for build VMs.  A new property,
alm.hudson.compute.boot.from.nds, is added to control this behavior.
The default value is true.  Using boot from NDS requires starting an
additional boot storage volume large enough to hold the VM image, which
takes some time.  The payoff is that the instance starts faster, and we
no longer need to run the software installation on subsequent VM
startup.

In order to implement this, new methods were added to the compute
service API to get the ImageListEntry and MachineImage objects.  These
objects are necessary in order to look up the size of the image, so we
know how large a boot volume is needed.

The default build VM image is now
/oracle/public/oel_6.4-20GB_RE_15.4.1-237, which starts up much faster
than the previous 60GB VM image.

Use 'shell' mode (instead of 'exec' mode) when executing commands through SSH

 - The shell mode gives the 'interactive login shell', which reads and executes commands from /etc/profile.d/*.sh and /etc/environment.

 - The exec mode gives the 'non-interactive login shell, which does not read from /etc/profile.d/*.sh, but reads from ~/.bashrc.

 - Because TW software bundles define the environment variables at /etc/profile.d/*.sh and /etc/environment, the shell mode should be used.

 - Reference: http://askubuntu.com/questions/438150/scripts-in-etc-profile-d-being-ignored

19742: javax.naming.NameNotFoundException in production for some users

In spite of assurances otherwise, it turns out that the GUID for a
tenant can change.  Since DCS stores the tenant GUID in the profile
database, this can lead to DCS using the incorrect GUID for a tenant.
This causes NameNotFoundException from the LDAP when searching for user
or group roles, since it's looking in a tenant GUID that doesn't exist.
To guard against this, if we hit NameNotFoundException, force an LDAP
lookup of the tenant GUID and update the value stored in the database.

Record all build VM states in database

There were serveral states a build slave VM could be in that were not
recorded in the database.  This meant that state information could be
lost.  For example:

* When a build VM was returned from Hudson to the hub due to an error or
a deprovision request from the hub, this was not recorded in the
database. Rather, it just scheduled a job through JMS to move the VM to
the next state.  If this job were lost, the state would be lost.  There
are now two additional status constants to record these returned states
- DEPROVISION_RETURNED and ERROR_RETURNED.

* Build VMs were marked for deletion by setting the status to DELETED.
If a VM marked for deletion hit an error, this set the status to ERROR.
Both states could not be recorded at once, which could result in state
information being lost.  There is now a separate column to mark a build
VM as deleted, so both states can be recorded.

These changes ensure that the full state of a build VM can always be
estabilshed based on the database alone.  For example, if we lose JMS
messages, we can recreate them from the database.

Fix build slave deprovision flow

If the hub determines that a build slave needs to be deleted or
deprovisioned, any builds that are currently running should be allowed
to finish.  However, no new bulids should be scheduled on the slave.
Once any currently running builds are finished, the slave will then
become idle, and the retention strategy will return it to the hub for
deprovisioning.

Fix ProjectServiceBeanTest

The test uses ProjectTestUtilsBean.autoClean to attempt to delete all
test organizations.  This fails because there are organizations left
around as side effects of other tests.  Those organizations have
QuotaSetting instances pointing at them, which prevents the delete from
working.  Added a quick fix to get the test working again, which is to
delete all QuotaSetting before deleting all CloudDevOrganization.

The side effect comes from a recent change to create organization
metrics in a new transaction.  Typically, unit test database changes are
rolled back at the end of the test, but not if the changes occur in a
new transaction not owned by the test.  In this case, if
EMMetricsServiceTest was an example of a test with such a side effect.
Running this before ProjectServiceBeanTest would cause the latter to
fail.

Add ability to specify environment variables in software bundles

Software bundles can now supply metadata containing environment
variables.  This is needed by build to set environment variables on the
build VMs.  For example, an environment variable may specify the
location of the software.  That environment variable can then be
referenced in build job configurations to use the software.

Improve reliability of client calls to build compute

Change build compute methods called from the DCS client such that a
pessimistic lock is taken on the build slave instance, which avoids
OptimisticLockException if a background task happens to be working on
the same instance.  Also move any compute service calls to a background
job, rather than making those calls directly in response to DCS client
requests.

Re-implmented the VirtualMachineProvider for build to be simpler and
more efficient.

A DESTROYING state for build VMs is added, which resolves an issue where
a VM would be shown as "VM Stopped", then if you deleted it, it would
change to "VM Stopping".  It will now show "Deleting VM", which is a
more sensible progression of states.

Fix race condition when checking compute enabled on Hudson startup

On Hudson startup, a periodic background task is started to update the
DCS organization compute status.  The initial delay of that task is 0,
but there was a race condition between start of that task and the first
call which needed the compute status.  This intermittently caused the
DCS Hudson plugin to assume compute was not enabled, resulting in builds
using the static build VM pool instead of a compute VM.  This commit
adds synchronization to ensure that the compute status is always updated
before it is used.

Asynchronous software bundle installation

The software bundle framework formerly installed software bundles by
keeping an active SSH connection open between the hub and the compute VM
for the duration of the installation.  Software bundle installation can
take a very long time - up to a half hour or so for things like SOA
suite which require a very large (3.2GB) file download.  Keeping a
connection open between the hub and compute VM for that long is
problematic for several reasons.  First, it consumes resources on the
hub, such as threads.  We might have potentially hundreds of compute VMs
starting at once in production, so this could be a significant amount of
resources.  Second, it will fail if that hub goes down during that time.
And finally, it eventually hits the sshd timeout on the compute VM, so
the software install fails with a connection error after 15 minutes.

To resolve these problems, the software bundle installation is now
asynchronous.  A shell script is created from a template and uploaded to
the compute VM.  This is launched in the background.  The shell script
contains all the steps to install the bundles, including installing
Chef, downloading the bundles, and running Chef.  The log output, PID,
and exit status of the background process are all stored on the file
system of the compute VM.  A hub can periodically check back later (and
if JMS is used, any hub can do this check).  This check looks at the
exit status and PID to determine if the process is still running, using
information stored locally on the compute VM file system, so no database
data is needed to track this progress.  The check is also fairly fast
(just a couple of commands run on the VM).  So the hub connection to the
VM only needs to be periodically open for a short time.

The BundleInstaller API provides a method to perform this check.  It is
up to callers of the API to periodically call this method to determine
if the installation is complete.  For convenience, a temporary method is
added for existing callers which calls this check in a loop as a
transitional mechanism.  This can be removed once all existing clients
move to the new asynchronous mechanism.
